PSP App User Guide

This guide will provide documentation on some of the available functions in the application. The following sections describe the various ways to view, filter and maneuver around the data to aide in analysis.

Navbar

The navbar allows users to navigate between the data analysis and reference information panes. Click on “Data Summaries” or “References” to choose which pane is active. Any changes to your parameter selections will not be lost while navigating between navbar panes.

Clicking on the title, “Pesticide Stewardship Partnerships”, will open a new window with the main PSP project page on the Oregon Department of Agriculture website.

Data Analysis

Sidebar

The sidebar allows users to filter the data shown in the data analysis panes. To hide the sidebar, click the button. The following sections describe the inputs available in the sidebar.

Years

Users can use the slider input to choose the date range (by year) that is used in the data analysis panes. Slide the two circular buttons forward or back on the scale to change the upper and lower limits of the date range.

Clicking on the button will animate the plots by increasing the upper and lower year limits by one every few seconds.

Note: some views may re-render during animation causing edited plots (titles, axis, etc.) to reset.

Basin

Click on a basin to focus the data on for analyis. All of the data will be filtered for the selected basin. A map of the basin will appear on the bottom of the sidebar.

Plots

The app includes various plots that allow the data to be viewed based on different parameters. Most of these plots include some interactive functions described in the following sections.

Hover

Hovering over the data on the plots will show data related to the bars or points nearest the cursor. Stacked bar charts will show the data of each bar related to that x-axis value.

Editing Plots

Titles

Titles can be edited by clicking on the title and entering the desired text. Adding “< b >” before and “< /b >” (with the spaces removed) after your text will attach a bold font.

Axes

Click and drag on either the x or y axis to move the plot view along the chosen axis. Click and drag on either end of the axis to move only that end of the axis. Clicking on either end of an axis will give the option to change the value of the limit of that end of the axis. Note: if the axis contains text values, the value will be the nth value in the arrangement of the axis.

Legends

Clicking on the legend titles will allow for the text to be changed. Clicking the color or symbol associated with the series will turn it “off”, removing its visibility on the plot (shown with semi-transparent legend entry). Clicking it again turn the series back on.

Hover Bar

With the cursor hovering over the plot, a toolbar will appear at the top right of the plot window. The most notable features in this bar are the two camera buttons that will download the current view of the plot to your computer.

Detection Map

The detection map displays pesticide detection data spatially and contains multiple layers that allow the user to compare the results based on location, estimated crop types, etc. Use the drop down boxes to choose the analyte and aquatic life ratio range to display on the map.

The basins selected via the sidebar will be displayed on the map along with detections that match the selections from the drop down list. To see the available layers to add or remove, click on the symbol. Check the boxes of the desired layers and they will be added to the map.

If there are many detections within a certain area, they will be grouped together with a circle marker containing their sum total of detections. Clicking on the marker will zoom to the extent of those detections. Detections will be grouped until they can be separated by monitoring station. At this point, clicking on a circle will show the detections “exploded” in a spiral around the station as in the figure below.

Hovering over each circle will show the ALR and sampling date of that detection. The colors represent the same percentage of the benchmark that they do in the detection frequency plots and can be seen as factors in the legend at the bottom right of the detection map.

On the top right of the map there are full screen and search buttons. The search button allows the station to be searched by name. Selecting the station from the list that appears will zoom the map to that station location. The full screen button will display the map across the entire available screen size, but will lose some functionality. The expand button provides an alternative to the full screen that still allows full access to the inputs and selectors provided by the app. The detection map can be reverted to its original size by hitting the button again.

Subplots

Clicking on any single element of the basins, stations or detections layers will produce a plot of the ALRs for the selected analyte and the estimated upstream land use at that location. Clicking on a basin will produce an additional plot of the estimated percentages of various crop categories throughout the area. The plots can be found directly below the detection map.

Layers

The available layers provide additional reference information to support the detection results. The basemap can be changed between street maps and world aerial imagery. The Detections and Basins layers are on by default but can be turned on or off by clicking their respective checkboxes. The Streams and Stations layers will show you the location and names of NHD streamlines and PSP monitoring stations. Hovering over a station will give you the station description. The Land Use layer will show the National Land Cover Database 2011 cell by cell estimates of land use derived from spectro-imaging analysis. Click the link above the detection map for descriptions of what land use each color represents.

Note: clearcuts were classified as shrubland or grassland due to its vegetation heights and will fall into the “other” catagory in the land use summary charts, underrepresenting the percent of forest land.

The Crops layer will overlay a raster of the USDA crop estimates derived from spectro-imaging analysis. Clicking on a cell will give the estimated crop type/category for that location via a popup that appears on the top right of the map. This popup can be moved by dragging it to another location. Click the link above the detection map to see a legend of all the crop types/categories represented by the layer.

Note: These layers are intended to help the user get an idea of the landscape surrounding the monitoring stations and is not intended to suggest sources of pesticides found in the waters.

References

The Reference section of the Navbar provides some helpful information to support the data analysis and add context to the results. The glossary of terms provides general definitions of some of the vocabulary used throughout the app with equations for calculations or links for sources and/or more information. The analyte descriptions give some general info on the more common pollutant ingredients detected throughout the PSPs. There is also an additional station reference section that provides a lookup table to search for station IDs, descriptions or associated project basin.
